It was a family tradition on my birthday growing up that *I* got to answer the family phone whenever it rang. 80% of the time it was family and friends calling to wish me a happy birthday, but a good 20% of the time it would be sales calls or people needing to talk to my parents about something very much non-my-birthday related. I didn't let that stop me. "It's my birthday" I would announce, to the confused grown up on the other end, refusing to hand over the phone until they at the very least wished me a happy birthday and asked me how I would be celebrating. I lived for the phone tradition, every ring of the phone filling my little heart with joy and excitement. Fast forward to today where I feel even keeping my phone on vibrate is too intrusive which is why I have had it on silent/do not disturb for the past 6+ years and deleted my birthday from my FB account because dealing with birthday greetings just sounds like a LOT.

When I was in high school I interviewed at the Aeropostale at the Denver West Mall in Lakewood, CO. The interview was set smack dab in the middle of the crowded mall food court. The interviewees were 8-12 terrified teenagers including ✨moi✨ and the interviewers, you ask? They worked through a few "greatest strength/weaknesses" perfunctory questions filled with exaggerated eye rolls at every answer before getting into the real meat of the interview. "Ok. For your next question... we want you to stand up on the table (reminder we are in the middle of a crowded mall food court) and sing." Amber said, a look of evil glee spreading across her beautiful orange face. "Or you can like tell me about someone who inspires you, but if you choose that option, we WILL look down on you for that." (I wish I was kidding). 

The terrified interviewees shared stories about their moms and teachers and grandparents who inspired them before it got to my turn at which point I climbed atop the food court table, sang approximately 6 seconds of Jojo's Leave (Get Out), and then sat back down in my seat. 
Later that evening I got a call that I would be starting the next day. I was the only one in my interview group to get the job. I would go on to spend the next 4 months in employed Aeropostale bliss, rocking the shit out of *multiple* monkey studded layered pastel polos (thank you 15% employee discount wut wut) before quitting for a job at American Eagle. #bless

A song was preferable. I lived for the phone tradition, every ring of the phone filling my little heart with joy and excitement. Fast forward to today where I feel even keeping my phone on vibrate is too intrusive which is why I have had it on silent/do not disturb for the past 6+ years and deleted my birthday from my FB account because dealing with birthday greetings just sounds like a LOT.

Elementary memory that haunts me to this day: The year? 1995. The grade? Third. The day? ✨Valentine’s Day✨. Something about those little cardboard rectangles that I had spent hours over deciding which of the kids would get the good ones featuring Timon and Pumba and which kids would get the Scar ones which were objectively the worst valentine in the box just made me feel so alive, you know? 

I arrived at school only to find out that the party was a half day party, not the full day that I had anticipated. I also learned that before the card distribution ceremony could commence, we had our weekly spelling test, a test that I had assumed would be delayed due to the party and had, as a result, not studied for. Panic. 

Despite having lost sleep the night before due to excitement over the gala, I knew that I’d rather miss the party than risk failing a test. I approached my teacher, a stern lady named Miss Williams (a true weirdo who insisted on coming to our homes for parent teacher conferences and once made me cry because she didn’t like the new way I was trying to train myself to write the number 2, smdh), and as I began to rattle down the lengthy list of symptoms I was currently pretending to experience, I could see in her eyes that she saw right through the BS and knew I hadn’t studied for the test. Overcorrecting mid-course, I quickly tacked on a “so I’d like to go to the clinic … after we take the test.”

This is how, dear reader, I both failed a test *and* missed the party of my third grade lifetime all within a single fateful day. 

Whew. Looks like I have a lot to unpack today.

I had a Nokia brick by the end of high school and had phones with almost the same level of functionality in college. Advances in cell phone technology at that time were pretty much the brick turning into a flip phone and the flip phone turning into a razor flip phone before turning back into a brick but this time with a slide out qwerty keyboard so you didn't have to tap the number 7 a whopping four whole times to get the letter S. Games would improve slightly (though nothing would ever beat the OG Snake), you could eventually take the grainiest of photos, and we went from having just beeps as ringtones that vaguely resembled a top 40 hit to actual songs. 

A few friends had early iPhones by the time I graduated college in 2009, but even then, the Internet wasn't really set up for people to do all that much on it with their phones. Social media was still something we did on our laptops and nothing went viral. WiFi wasn't super available and data plans were astronomically expensive, so going on the internet with your phone was a panic attack waiting to happen as the time required to wait for something to load had the very real potential of ✨bankrupting your family✨. 

In 2015, I started teaching university students. Our experiences in college, though only 6 years apart, really could not have been more different. How they connected with each other, their teachers and their studies, how they branded and expressed themselves, what they were proud of and what caused stress and anxiety… all of it was night and day to what I had experienced in college. And while there are undoubtedly major benefits to life with a smart phone, I am so deeply thankful to have made it through all of childhood without one. It's insane how quickly everything changed and, realizing that we were the last generation to have childhoods that didn't come with smartphones and social media, I can’t help but think that we are super lucky to have had that experience.

Christmas 2000, our BIG gift was a family computer. Life was never the same. Here are some of my internet firsts for your skimming pleasure: 

My first internet search was “handsome famous man”. The first site was a Pierce Brosnan fanpage with a header reading “Hunk Pierce Brosnan”. I didn’t know what “Hunk” meant and assumed this was his first name. I thusly went through life for a somewhat extended period of time announcing to anyone who would listen that my favorite actor was a one mister Hunk Pierce Brosnan

The first video I ever watched online was the music video for Spice Girls, Two Become One. I am not exaggerating when I tell you that the video took 5+ hours to fully load, during which time no one in the house could use the phone. I would run back to the computer every 10 minutes to see if another second or two of the video was now watchable. I still have every word to that song memorized... yet somehow didn’t grasp the meaning of any of the lyrics for like two full decades after? 

Another early search resulted in the first ever Internet scam that I, a then 12 year old with zero internet savvy and questionable critical thinking skills, fell for hook line and sinker (I’d guess some of you did too?) -the Bonsai Kitten, described on Wikipedia as, “a hoax website that claimed to instruct readers how to raise a kitten in a jar, so as to mold the bones of the kitten into the shape of the jar as the cat grows in the same way as a bonsai plant.” ... I opened my parents’ phone book and, SOBBING, called any number I could find for any business that had the word “animal” in their name to let them all know about the horrors of the fictional Bonsai (which I pronounced bone-ass-see) Kitten. My parents stopped me before I called 911 but let me tell you, I wasn’t far from it. 

Thankfully all issues with the internet were fixed shortly after and nothing whacky happens anymore #bless
